                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     SPORT BRIEFS
                                                              
	India, Pak situations different:  Morgan  Mohali: The International Cricket Council (ICC) president David Morgan on Sunday expressed hopes that the cancellation of India rsquo;s tour to Pakistan would not have any adverse effect on the 2011 World Cup.  Four countries mdash; India, Pakistan, Sri Lanka and Pakistan mdash; are slated to jointly host the World Cup in 2011.  Addressing a press conference here, Morgan said: ldquo;There has to be some concern about the next World Cup. But we are confident that among them, we would have a good World Cup. rdquo;  The ICC chief said situations in India and Pakistan were different.  ldquo;Pakistan is a different country. Quite clearly, the security experts said India is safe and secure (for England) to return but that is not the case with Pakistan, rdquo; Morgan said.    
	ECB plan  London: England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) on Sunday hinted that it was in the process of having a mutual agreement with the Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) on the conduct of Indian Premier League (IPL).  ECB said in a statement that it had held discussions with the BCCI at Mohali during the ongoing second Test and will have further discussions in January next year.    
	 Dar admission  Melbourne: Umpire Aleem Dar has admitted that he erred in giving Matthew Hayden out in the first Test against South Africa in Perth. ldquo;I got it wrong. I thought it was an inside edge but it wasn rsquo;t. I thought Matthew was very good about it, rdquo; he said.     
	 Surya on top  Mangalore: Surya Sekhar Ganguly drew with Sriram Jha of LIC to maintain his lead by a full point, while Parimarjan Negi joined teammate Satyapragyan at the second position at the end of Round V of the 46th National A Chess Championship Sunday.    
	 Mary wins  New Delhi: Top seed Tania Sachdev and Mary Ann Gomes defeated Kiran Manisha Mohanty and Pon N Krithika respectively in Round IV of the 35th Parsvnath National Women Chess Championship on Sunday.    
	 Shiv tied 10th   Bangkok: Shiv Kapur was the lone Indian to sign off inside top-10 after a steady final-round two-under 70 helped him grab a share of the 10th spot at the Asian Tour rsquo;s season-ending Volvo Masters of Asia on Sunday.     
	 Holyfield loses  Zurich: WBA champion Nikolai Valuev won a majority points decision against four-times world champion Evander Holyfield on Saturday to end the American rsquo;s hopes of becoming the oldest ever title-holder.     
	 PP Singh best  Jaipur: Captain Param Pal Singh emerged champion in the skeet event of the national shooting championship (Shotgun) at the Jagatpura range here Sunday.
    
